{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:17:12.017027+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T18:17:12.606356+00:00", "id": 19668424, "conceptrecid": "19668423", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668424", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668423", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19668424", "metadata": {"title": "Assessing the performance of nonparametric estimators of species richness in meadows", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668424", "publication_date": "2010", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) To accurately measure the number of species in a biological community, a complete inventory should be performed, which is generally unfeasible; hopefully, estimators of species richness can help. Our main objectives were (i) to assess the performance of nonparametric estimators of plant species richness with real data from a small set of meadows located in the Basque campin\u02dca (northern Spain), and (ii) to apply the best estimator to a larger dataset to test the effects on plant species richness caused by environmental conditions and human practices. Two non-asymptotic and seven asymptotic accumulation functions were fitted to a randomized sample-based rarefaction curve computed with data from three well sampled meadows, and information theoretic methods were used to select the best fitting model; this was the Morgan-Mercer-Flodin, and its asymptote was taken as our best guess of true richness. Then, five nonparametric estimators were computed: ICE, Chao 2, Jackknife 1 and 2, and Bootstrap; MMRuns and MMMeans were also assessed. According to the criteria set for our performance assessment (i.e., bias, precision, and accuracy), the best estimator was Jackknife 1. Finally, Jackknife 1 was applied to assess the effects of terrain slope and soil parent material, and also fertilization, grazing, and mowing, on plant species richness from a larger dataset (20 meadows). Results suggested that grass cutting was causing a loss of richness close to 30%, as compared to unmowed meadows. It is concluded that the use of nonparametric estimators of species richness can improve the evaluation of biodiversity responses to human management practices.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Gonz\u00e1lez-Oreja, Jos\u00e9 Antonio", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Garbisu, Carlos", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Mendarte, Sorkunde", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Ibarra, Ainhoa", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Albizu, Isabel", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/db956200f61657bee1928532e3d5c3dc", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/8e66e6a8da701dedca19ed1beb4d1c5cbe61ea207dc9af4d47fe857050d6aeae", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/VCIUA4NU", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/VCIUA4NU", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/2f2ab8f2f5660300a041cc9df2bd7976!/b338174-340649", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/0157e8ec3f1f8eb877e7b6cd6fde26bc", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "5", "pages": "1417-1436", "title": "Biodiversity and Conservation", "volume": "19"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/db956200f61657bee1928532e3d5c3dc"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:VCIUA4NU"}, {"identifier": "10.1007/s10531-009-9770-8"}], 